answers.body_markdown:
The cumulative probability (&lt;= x) of a Poisson random variable can be calculated by:

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

In your case, x is 2 and you want to find lambda (the mean) such that this is 0.5. You can [type this into WolframAlpha][2] and have it solve it for you. So rather than an optimisation problem, this is just a root-finding problem (though one could argue that optimisation problems _are_ just finding roots.)

You can also do this with Apache Commons Maths, with one of the [root finders][3].

    int maximumGoals = 2;
    double expectedProbability = 0.5;
    UnivariateFunction f = x -&gt; {
      double sum = 0;
      for (int i = 0; i &lt;= maximumGoals; i++) {
        sum += Math.pow(x, i) / CombinatoricsUtils.factorialDouble(i);
      }
      return sum * Math.exp(-x) - expectedProbability;
    };

